@*
    About page. Scott's strongest honest card: 25 years, ex-agency, direct. Copy is
    placeholder and heavily his to write, especially the personal narrative. Every claim
    baked in here is BACKED (25 years .NET, agency background, direct, backend depth,
    Jambalam). Do NOT invent biography: employers, schools, hometown, dates. Those are
    marked as prompts for Scott to fill, not written for him.
*@

<section class="section--lede">
    <div class="container container--prose">
        <p class="topper">About</p>
        <h1 class="header">Scott Neidig</h1>
        <p class="text lede__text">
            Web and application developer on the Colorado Front Range, with 25 years of .NET
            behind me. I work directly with businesses and organizations on the systems they
            run on.
        </p>

        @*
            Optional headshot. A face builds trust on an about page, but it's not required and
            it's Scott's to add. Drop the image in wwwroot and uncomment:
            <img class="about__photo" src="~/img/scott.jpg" alt="Scott Neidig" width="240" height="240" decoding="async" />
        *@
    </div>
</section>

<section class="section--alt">
    <div class="container container--prose">
        <p class="topper">Background</p>
        <h2 class="title">Where I come from</h2>
        <p class="text">
            @* PROMPT for Scott: the narrative. How you got into development, the kind of work
               you did at agencies, what you're known for. Keep it plain and true. Backed facts
               to draw on: 25 years .NET, agency experience, senior-level. Don't overclaim. *@
            [Your story goes here. Twenty-five years of building and maintaining .NET
            applications, much of it inside agencies. Write it in your own voice.]
        </p>
    </div>
</section>

<section>
    <div class="container container--prose">
        <p class="topper">How I work</p>
        <h2 class="title">Direct, and on the hard part</h2>
        <p class="text">
            No agency layer between you and the person doing the work. I take on the back end,
            the database, the business logic, the parts that actually solve the problem, not
            just the page on top. It's where a real application pulls ahead of a template, and
            it's the work I've done for years.
        </p>
        <p class="text">
            That includes AI where it earns its place. I've built it into a live product,
            Jambalam, as a working feature people use.
        </p>
    </div>
</section>

<section class="section--alt">
    <div class="container container--prose">
        <p class="topper">Proof</p>
        <h2 class="title">See the work</h2>
        <p class="text">
            The clearest picture of what I do is what I've built.
        </p>
        <p>
            <a asp-controller="Work" asp-action="Index">Have a look at my work</a>
        </p>
    </div>
</section>

<partial name="_CallToAction" model="@("Want to talk about your project?")" />
